heat in eastern Washington i inherited 200 i was talking to my uncle and this is the Paloo country in eastern Washington that used to have 20 feet deep top soils that blew from eastern Oregon you know over 10,000 years you know from the volcanoes and the winds deposited the polls and now that 20 ft of top soil shrunk to about you know 12 in 10 in uh because of repetitive farming so he went to no till um my cousin actually did went to no till and he said and the no till practice basically you're not you're not plowing the fields he said there was a loss of production for the first few years until the carbon was built up and now because of no till farming he's regenerating so regen agriculture is a key but you have to pay the expense of investment of actually having fewer returns in profitability for a period of time until you hit that sustainable threshold where it becomes more economical i I think that's a general rule is that we have to have patient capitalism patient investors we need to look beyond the time horizon of our immediate return on investment and accept a longer time horizon is there like ways to introduce mycelium into farming practices not just happening all the time happening all the time you It happens in forestry too you can't go to a nursery without getting microisal fungi uh in soils i mean go to go any go out in your local nursery and get a bail of soil it's all with microised so that's that's wonderful because they with the microisy and these other fungi that are introduced it increases the host defense immunity of the plant so it's not susceptible to insect paratization there's a fungus called metarisium that's in grasses why aren't all grasses consumed by insects because this enopathogenic fungus that's a fungus that kills insects is also an endapy that's growing inside of grasses so using the endopitic fungi that have a natural anti-insect predation property means you don't have to use as many asides this story I'm telling you repeats a hundred a thousand times and this is why the field of micology I believe should be funded as much as the field of the computer sciences this is why we need a huge new generational uh shift uh towards environmental science using fungi because it's applicable it's sustainable it's scalable and it's immediate um that that to me is is not something that's a pie in the sky concept it's a deliverable that we can deliver you know literally this next next season does it have applications to uh clothing yeah Stella McCartney is really big on that stella Paul McCartney's daughter so yeah they're also clothing and look at my hat my hat's made from this amadu mushroom this is called German felt you put this mushroom into water with ashes for two weeks and you can pull it apart to make this hat and this hat was made by some people in Transylvania um so it's a tradition that's gone over several hundred years this allowed for the portability of fire so this was a an appropriate technology can put embers of a fire in this mushroom and carry it for days so by the way if there's a spark that gets onto this hat it's like a fuse the whole hat will burn up whoa so it's um Aadoo is the name so it revolutionized warfare napoleonic times this was the when the spark from the flint went into the punk it was made of amadu that's where fuses came from so Aadu has a history going back to all the way back to Hypocrates 420 BC u as an anti-inflammatory again these mushrooms have a multiplicity of benefits so it's an anti-inflammatory for carrying fire to making garments and it's also used for smoking around beehives to sub subdue the bees for hundreds of years amadu was used also for being able to calm bees down and we found that to have extremely strong immuno benefiting properties that reduces the deformed wing virus which is sweeping the planet i published in my colleagues from the USDA and Washington State University in nature scientific reports the title of the article is extracts of polyore mushrooms reduce be uh viruses and honeybees uh the altmetric score is extremely high but that is a natural product it's not an antiviral drug it upregulates innate immunity so look it up nature scientific reports extract for polyom mushrooms reduce viruses and honeybees that's the tip of the proverbial iceberg of how these can upregulate your innate immunity to be able to fight fight diseases i mean it's amazing um last question on this topic any application for fuel as a bio um available and renewable fuel source i went down that rabbit hole we produced a I call like ethanol yeah but I have to admit it was not as efficient as other fermentation technologies using like uh sacroyces survei you know mixed beer alcohol yeast there's many other microorganisms that are more from my limited experience prove me wrong there could be some out there that are superstars and that's with the importance of microiversity um so yeah I was not able to I couldn't uncover the species that was a hyper producer of of uh of alcohol or hydrocarbon based fuels not just alcohol so um that's again there's not enough time in life to do all these things to explore before we let you go um you know we we'd love to just ask you to to uh as concisely as you'd like to um what is the message that you believe you were placed here to share with people well the message I'd like to share is that we are born into this beautiful life that we share kindness and forgiveness and cooperation builds communities that are healthier stronger our descendants are depending upon us to make the best decisions our ancestors gave us this opportunity we're all part of one giant consciousness all religions are steering towards the same unanimity of being it makes me feel better about my own mortality that I'm going to enter into this state of unonymity and whatever religious or spiritual discipline that you're following we're all in this together and it's a great thing it's absolutely beautiful um as I said I've been waiting a long time to get to to meet you and um it's just such a pleasure and I think you're the greatest spore that has ever been produced by this planet so um thank you so much for being here with us well bless you both and thank you all and you know be kind random acts of kindness are really important and they're practical in the long run be forgiving you know take a deep breath go out in nature enjoy life we We brought mushroom hats um that Valerie gave us to show our love for you i'm so curious what he would talk to us about if we spoke to him again he was dropping little little hints what did he say what about his 80 milligram microgram macrogram i don't know his hero dose with superhero dose growing new neurons with a therapist i know no but it sounds like there was more going on in there he's pretty much a believer that um there's life on other planets maybe mycelium life i I I mean yes i think I think the thing that we didn't really get to which I think rounds out a little bit more of the person who is Paul Stamuts is you know a tremendous amount of the the work that he does is in understanding myium fungi and mushrooms psilocybin is one part of that but he believes that there's basically a a pharmaceutical cabinet that nature has provided us that can help with with arthritis with aging with depression with anxiety even at low doses i mean even outside of the journey experience these mushrooms are nature's medicine and that's a huge component of of the work that he does the company that he has as well we have a friend of the podcast who wants to come back on and talk about new breaking research on the impact and how inflammation is really at the core root of all the afflictions basically that anyone can have whether it be depression anxiety irritable bowel syndrome arthritis even links to dementia and Alzheimer's disease all related to an underlying inflammation and what he was talking about is using mcelium and nature natural approaches to addressing that core