row I can grow those um you know you can this is it's a fermentation technology so this may seem extraordinary but it's true but a piece of tissue from a mushroom the size of my little fingernail here in 6 months I can grow 10 million pounds of mushrooms of of mcelium and about 1 million compounds of mushrooms about 10% of the of the micelium becomes mushrooms so I mean exponential expansion of myial mass because all these networks are growing out and they're constantly forking and forking and forking and they grow in fermentation three-dimensionally so you have the like the starburst you know little galaxies of mcelium uh growing out so the mycelial uh systems on this on this planet as far as we know there could be other systems there's a saprophitic ones that grow on dead material also called soprobic uh mushroom species oyster mushrooms shiakei maki mushrooms ininoi mushrooms they're all all the saprophitic gourmet mushrooms that people can can can grow also psilocybin mushrooms are saprophitic mushrooms or sap probic mushrooms there are parasitic mushrooms these like the honey mushroom the largest organism known in the world is a honey mushroom in eastern Oregon 2,200 acres in size one contiguous mycelial mat but that can kill the trees but then it can grow saprophitically so it can be both a parasite and a sacrify I think they're meadow makers they destroy the forests the forest decline you know grasslands occur uncles come in elk deer etc it's a ray way of the system recharging then there is the microisal species which many of people know Merlin Sheldrick you know and Suzanne Samard have written some great books on microisal fungi on the communication of these networks helping diverse tree species from deciduous trees to conifer trees birectional flow of nutrients to sustain the ecosystem of the forest um and then there are the endophidic mushroom species and these are really great and it may be the majority of the benefits from plants that have been isolated 